At the end of this the top two teams, Harvard Friggin' Huge and Cornell, were tied at 24 Sumerian Love Poems apiece, and they played against each other in a 30 tossup Battle Royale. [Cornell had defeated HFH in the full round robin 185-180. Harvard evened the score in the bracket match-up, 375-175.]

Harvard Friggin' Huge defeated Cornell 370-185 to win the Northeast Regional ACF championship.

Congratulations to Harvard for their victory, and to Cornell for making the finals.

Midwest

The ACF Midwest Regional Championship was held this weekend at the University of Chicago. Teams were divided into 2 divisions, in which round robins were played, with the top 4 from each moving on to a playoff RR. The top 2 teams then played a best 2-of-3 final. Tiebreaker was point differential, because I was finally convinced not to use head-to-head by the argument on the qb list last month.

Stats follow, but first:

The tournament ran an hour ahead of the planned schedule. This is purely due to wonderful teams & a wonderful volunteer (well, they got pizza...) staff. Thank you to everyone who helped out, including moderators Alice Chou, John Edwards, Mitchell Szczepanczyk, Lorin Burte, Eric Hillemann, John Tangren, and a guy from BGSU whose name I cannot recall (very very sorry.). A special huge thank you to Mike Altman, statkeeper extraordinaire, who had new stats up after _every_ round, on time.

On to results:

In the final, Chicago A beat Illinois Malignant 360-60 & 235-230.

Nick Fossland of Chicago $ won the Rob Getz award for highest TU/I ratio, min 10 PPG. (he was 29-0) For his efforts he won the traditional U of C coffee mug.

Southeast

The 1999 ACF SE Regional was held this past weekend with 16 teams from 12 schools participating. We'd like to thank our readers at the tournament: Scott Gillispie, Chris Moody, David Leach, James Quintong, Cory Edwards, Mike Pietrucha, and Kyle along with the tournament director, Albert Whited.

Congratulations to the University of South Carolina for winning the tournament. Kentucky, Berry, and Vandy A finished with identical 13-2 records and were 1-1 versus each other. Kentucky finished second because they scored more points in their matches vs. the other 2 teams that were tied. Below are the final team standings in correct order.

Individual Stats

We awarded All-Stars to the top six finishers, all of whom averaged over 40 points per game. Congratulations to Jason King from Georgia who took home top individual honors and a huge book on the world of art. TC Ford from South Carolina A took home 2nd place individual honors and also chose an art book with Pop Art as its subject. Matt Schneller from Vanderbilt A finished 3rd and chose a book of short stories.

Al Przygocki from Georgia State finished 4th and chose a world atlas of history. Kelly Mackenzie from Kentucky finished 5th and chose a book on operas. Seth Kendall, also from Kentucky, finished 6th and won a classical music CD with music from the Baroque period. Below are the final individual standings after Round 17.

West

There was a circle of death between Stanford Asmodeus, BYU Albigenses, and Berkeley Asimov, each 6-1 after the first round-robin among all the teams.

The second, bracketed round robins (3 brackets, 3 teams each) broke the circle of death, with Stanford up one game over BYU going into the playoffs.

Stanford won the playoffs 425-80, and won ACF Regionals 1999 - West Coast. Congratulations to a very fine team!
